But it was impossible to maintain this uncompromising idealism in practice. The later Stolos found themselves compelled to admit that apart from virtue and vice, the absolute good and evil, there were preferenoes to be made among things indifferent, from which it followed that besides perfectly virtuous actions (κατορθώματα) there was a subordinate class of appropriate actions (καθήκοντα).
